#Text=Humphrey Fenn
#Text=Humphrey Fenn ( died 1634 ) , was an English puritan divine .
#Text=Life
#Text=Fenn was matriculated as sizar of Queens ' College , Cambridge , on 12 November 1568 , and graduated B.A. in 1573 .
#Text=He migrated to Peterhouse , and graduated M.A. in 1576 . [ 1 ]
#Text=In the same year he began his ministry at Northampton , and at once got into trouble for his nonconformity , and was committed to gaol .
#Text=The inhabitants of Northampton petitioned Queen Elizabeth for his release , giving him a high character as a preacher and a loyal subject .
#Text=On 21 Feb. 1578 he succeeded Anthony Fletcher as vicar of Holy Trinity , Coventry , and became a prominent man in the party headed by Thomas Cartwright ( 1535 – 1603 ) .
#Text=At the request of the London puritans he accompanied the Earl of Leicester to represent their grievances to the queen .
#Text=On the issue of Whitgift 's three articles ( 1583 ) , he refused to subscribe .
#Text=He was cited to Lambeth ( 1584 ) , and suspended .
#Text=An account of his examination is given by Brook , from Roger Morrice 's manuscript .
#Text=His place was taken by ‘ one Griffen , a Welchman , ’ between whom and Fenn , according to the manuscript city annals , there was ‘ a great contention ’ for the vicarage in 1584 or 1585 .
#Text=Fenn was restored to his vicarage shortly after 14 July 1585 , through the intercession of Leicester .

#Text=But in 1590 he was again suspended , owing to the active part which he took in the ‘ associations ’ of the Warwickshire puritan divines , was committed to the Fleet by the high commission , with Cartwright and others , and , refusing the purgation by oath , was deprived .
#Text=His successor , Richard Eaton , was instituted on 12 Jan. 1591 .
#Text=On 13 May Fenn and his companions were brought before the Star-chamber .
#Text=Articles , dealing mainly with their ‘ book of discipline , ’ were exhibited against them .
#Text=They denied that in their ‘ associations ’ they exercised any jurisdiction , or meddled with sedition .
#Text=Fenn ‘ seemed more stiff than Cartwright . ’
#Text=The Star-chamber remanded them without bail .
#Text=James VI of Scotland interceded ( 12 June ) for their release ; on 4 Dec. they petitioned for bail ; Fenn 's signature stands second in the list , immediately after Cartwright 's .
#Text=In April 1592 they again petitioned for release , this time successfully .
#Text=( Leicester 's letter of thanks is dated 21 May . )
#Text=Fenn returned to Coventry , and resumed his ministry , probably preaching only on week-days .
#Text=On 24 April 1624 ‘ Mr. Humphrey Fenn , preacher , ’ was appointed to the Sunday lectureship at St. John the Baptist 's ( Bablake ) .
#Text=This was a new lectureship ; the church , which had been in ruins , was repaired in 1608 , and a week-day lectureship established in favour of John Oxenbridge .
#Text=In 1626 or soon after ‘ old Mr. Fenn ’ joined with the mayor and leading citizens in inviting Samuel Clarke ( 1599 – 1683 ) , the martyrologist , to become a lecturer at Coventry .
#Text=This is the last notice of Fenn .
#Text=Tong says that he ‘ spent above forty years ’ with the Coventry people ; we must correct this to ‘ above fifty , ’ even if we deduct his enforced absences .
#Text=He died early in 1633 – 4 , and was buried on 8 Feb. in Holy Trinity churchyard , Coventry .
#Text=He seems to have had a son and grandson of the same name .

#Text=His will , made in 1631 , was prefaced by ‘ so full and so open a protestation against the hierarchy and the ceremonies , that the prelatical party would not suffer it to be put among the records of the court when the will was tendred to be proved ’ ( Clark , in Life of Julines Herring ) .
#Text=On 21 Feb. 1634 a copy of the introduction to the will of ‘ Humphrey Fen the eldest ’ was received by Archbishop Laud from the bishop of Coventry and Lichfield .
#Text=This preamble ( only ) was printed as ‘ The Last Will and Testament with the Profession of Faith of Humphrey Fenn , ’ &c . , 1641 , sm . 8vo ( no place of printing ) .
